Welcome to notebook eleven of the Java track. The topic for this session is Spring Boot in production. The previous three Spring notebooks gave us a working application. This notebook is what turns that application into something you can actually deploy and run reliably. Spring Core wired the components. Spring Web exposed them over hypertext transfer protocol. Spring Data persisted state. Spring Boot in production makes the whole thing operable.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, what Spring Boot adds on top of plain Spring, and what at sign Spring Boot Application actually means under the hood. Auto configuration, the mechanism that wires beans based on what is on the classpath. Externalised configuration in depth, including the precedence chain among property sources. At sign Configuration Properties with validation. Actuator, the operational endpoint set that exposes health, metrics, environment, beans, and more, along with how to write custom endpoints. Structured logging with the s l f four j facade and Logback, including the j s o n output convention for production. The Spring Boot test slices, at sign Spring Boot Test, at sign Web Mvc Test, at sign Data Jpa Test, at sign Json Test. Mocking beans inside a slice test with at sign Mockito Bean. Testcontainers, for spinning up real databases in your integration tests. Messaging with the spring kafka library, including the producer template, the at sign Kafka Listener annotation, and the s e r d e configuration. Java Message Service and Spring AMQP for RabbitMQ in one paragraph each. Packaging your application as a fat jar, and the layered jar shape for Docker. And finally, container deployment, including the explicit Dockerfile approach and the much simpler Cloud Native Buildpacks built into Spring Boot.

Let us start with what Spring Boot adds on top of plain Spring. Plain Spring is a fantastic dependency injection container, but it leaves you to configure every part of the runtime. You pick a servlet container. You set up a dispatcher servlet. You register the j s o n converters. You wire the data source. You configure transaction management. None of this is hard. All of it is tedious, and it is the same tedious work in every project. Spring Boot is an opinionated meta framework on top of Spring that does all of that for you.

Three things Boot brings to the table. First, auto configuration, which looks at what is on your classpath and wires sensible defaults. Second, starter dependencies, which are curated bundles like spring boot starter web that pull in everything you need for a category of feature. Third, embedded servers, with Tomcat or Jetty or Undertow packaged inside your jar, so deployment is simply java dash jar.

The entry point is one annotation and one main method. You annotate a class with at sign Spring Boot Application, you write a main method that calls Spring Application dot run, and the application starts.

That single annotation at sign Spring Boot Application is itself three annotations rolled into one. At sign Spring Boot Configuration, which marks the class as a configuration class. At sign Component Scan, which scans the class's package and all sub packages for stereotype annotated classes. And at sign Enable Auto Configuration, which turns on auto configuration. That is the whole entry point. From here, Boot finds your components, applies its conditional auto configurations, starts the embedded server, and your service is up.

Now, auto configuration. How does it actually work. Boot ships dozens of auto configuration classes. Each one is a configuration class that is only active when certain conditions hold. The conditions are usually one of two things. This library is on the classpath. Or, no user defined bean of this type exists yet.

The mechanism is built from a family of at sign Conditional annotations. At sign Conditional On Class triggers when a specific class is present on the classpath. At sign Conditional On Missing Bean triggers when no bean of a given type is already defined. At sign Conditional On Property triggers when a configuration property is set, and optionally truthy. At sign Conditional On Web Application triggers when the application is running inside a servlet web context.

A typical auto configuration reads like this. If Data Source is on the classpath, and the user has not defined their own Data Source bean, register a Hikari Connection Pool backed Data Source built from the spring datasource properties. You override Boot's defaults simply by declaring your own bean. Your bean wins. The auto configured one is silently skipped.

To inspect what auto configurations fired and which ones did not, pass dash dash debug on the command line at startup, or hit the slash actuator slash conditions endpoint at runtime. Boot prints a positive matches versus negative matches report. This is invaluable when you are debugging why is this bean not being created, or why is the application picking the wrong implementation.

Now, externalised configuration. The same code should run in development, in staging, and in production, with different values for things like database urls, hypertext transfer protocol endpoints, and feature flags. Boot reads properties from many sources and merges them, with later sources overriding earlier ones. The precedence chain, from lowest to highest, runs roughly as follows. At sign Property Source annotations on configuration classes. Application properties or application y a m l on the classpath. Application dash profile y a m l when that profile is active. Operating system environment variables. Java system properties set with dash uppercase d. And command line arguments prefixed with dash dash.

Higher numbers win. In practice this means you commit safe defaults in application y a m l, you override per environment with environment variables, and you override per individual run with command line flags.

A useful fact. Spring normalises property names across the different sources. So spring dot datasource dot url in y a m l, uppercase SPRING underscore DATASOURCE underscore URL as an environment variable, dash dash spring dot datasource dot url on the command line, and dash uppercase d spring dot datasource dot url as a java virtual machine flag all bind to the same property. This is what makes the same jar portable across local development, Docker, and Kubernetes, without code changes.

For non trivial configuration, the right shape is a typed record annotated with at sign Configuration Properties. You group a prefix's worth of properties into one bean. You get integrated development environment autocomplete. And you can validate the values at startup, by adding the at sign Validated annotation and using bean validation constraints like at sign Not Blank, at sign Positive, at sign Min, and at sign Max.

The startup contract is strict. If a required property is missing, or if validation fails, the application fails to start with a clear error message. This is exactly what you want. Better a noisy boot failure than a silent misconfiguration that surfaces an hour into production traffic.

Two convenient built in conversions worth knowing. The Duration type is parsed from the standard i s o eight six oh one form, like uppercase p t thirty s for thirty seconds, or from the friendlier thirty s or five m. The Data Size type parses byte size literals like ten m b. Use these types directly in your configuration record, and Spring handles the parsing.

Now, the actuator. Add the dependency spring boot starter actuator to your project and you get a set of hypertext transfer protocol endpoints exposing the runtime's vitals. The defaults are conservative. Only slash actuator slash health is exposed by default. You opt into the rest by setting the management endpoints web exposure include property.

The endpoints you will use most are the following. Slash actuator slash health gives the overall health, plus per component health for things like the database, Redis, Kafka, and any custom indicators. Slash actuator slash info gives static information like the application name, version, and build time. Slash actuator slash metrics gives every Micrometer metric the application records. Slash actuator slash env gives every configuration property and its source, which is invaluable when you are debugging why is this value not what I expected. Slash actuator slash beans gives the entire application context bean graph. Slash actuator slash conditions gives the auto configuration match report. Slash actuator slash mappings gives every hypertext transfer protocol route the application handles. And slash actuator slash loggers lets you both view and change log levels at runtime, without a restart.

The slash actuator slash health endpoint is the one your load balancer or Kubernetes liveness probe polls. Spring auto generates separate slash health slash liveness and slash health slash readiness groups for Kubernetes style probes, which differentiate between is the application alive and is the application ready to serve traffic.

You can also write custom health indicators. Implement the Health Indicator interface, return Health dot up or Health dot down from the health method, and Spring includes your indicator in the slash health response. The example in the notebook is a Kafka health indicator that calls the admin client's list topics method and reports up if it succeeds within a timeout, down otherwise.

Metrics flow through Micrometer, Boot's metrics abstraction. Boot publishes java virtual machine metrics like heap usage and garbage collection times, hypertext transfer protocol server metrics like request count and latency percentiles, j d b c connection pool metrics like active connections and wait time, Kafka client metrics, and many more, all out of the box. You can scrape them via slash actuator slash prometheus, when the Prometheus registry is on the classpath, or push to any of Micrometer's supported back ends, including Datadog, New Relic, and CloudWatch.

Now, logging. Boot ships Logback as the default logging implementation, behind the s l f four j facade. Every Spring class uses s l f four j, and you should do the same in your own classes. Get a logger by calling Logger Factory dot get Logger with the class object.

Two pieces of style discipline save you from a lot of operational pain. First, use the curly brace placeholder, not plus concatenation. The s l f four j facade skips formatting at disabled levels, so a debug message with placeholders costs nothing when debug is off. Concatenation always pays the cost, even when the message is suppressed. Second, when you log an exception, pass the exception as the last argument with no placeholder for it. The s l f four j framework detects the exception and prints the stack trace.

Configure log levels with logging dot level dot some package equals DEBUG in your application y a m l, or change them at runtime via the slash actuator slash loggers endpoint. For production, use structured j s o n logging. The Logback Logstash Encoder, from the logstash logback encoder dependency, turns every log event into a j s o n line that log aggregators like Splunk, Elasticsearch, Loki, and Datadog can index and query efficiently.

Now, testing. Boot ships slice annotations that load only the part of the application context you need to test. Slice tests start much faster than full context tests, and they isolate the layer under test from the rest of the system.

At sign Spring Boot Test loads the full context, for true integration tests. At sign Web Mvc Test, parameterised with a controller class, loads only the web layer, including Spring m v c, Jackson, and security configuration. At sign Data Jpa Test loads only the j p a repositories and an in memory database. At sign Json Test loads only the Jackson configuration. At sign Rest Client Test, parameterised with a gateway class, loads only the hypertext transfer protocol client configuration and provides a Mock Rest Service Server for asserting outbound calls.

Inside a slice test, you mock the collaborators with at sign Mockito Bean. The at sign Mockito Bean annotation, which replaces the older at sign Mock Bean as of Boot three point four, substitutes a Mockito mock for a real bean in the application context. Use it to isolate the layer under test from its collaborators.

Two patterns worth internalising. First, default to slice tests. They are ten times faster than a full at sign Spring Boot Test, and they force you to write decoupled code. Second, reach for at sign Spring Boot Test only for end to end checks, like startup health checks, security wiring verification, and full request roundtrips through the whole stack.

In memory h two databases are fine for trivial repository tests, but the moment you use Postgres specific syntax, like j s o n b, full text search, or partial indexes, h two disagrees and your tests give false confidence. The right answer is Testcontainers. Testcontainers spins up a real Postgres in Docker for the duration of your test class, then tears it down. Your tests run against the same database technology as production.

The pattern uses at sign Testcontainers on the test class, a static container field annotated at sign Container, and a static method annotated at sign Dynamic Property Source that wires the container's connection url, username, and password into the application's spring datasource properties. Spring Boot three point one and later have first class Testcontainers support via the at sign Service Connection annotation, which lets you drop the annotation on a container bean and Boot wires the right spring properties automatically, with no manual property source method.

Testcontainers supports Postgres, MySQL, MongoDB, Kafka, Redis, RabbitMQ, Elasticsearch, LocalStack for Amazon Web Services, and dozens of others. It is the modern default for integration testing on the java virtual machine.

Now, messaging. Kafka is the dominant message bus in modern back ends. The spring kafka library gives you a Kafka Template for producing messages, and the at sign Kafka Listener annotation for consuming them. You configure the broker address, the s e r d e classes for keys and values, and the consumer group identifier in your application y a m l.

The pattern is the following. Define an event class. A record is the ideal shape for this, because the event is just a data carrier. Inject a Kafka Template, parameterised with the key type and the event type, into your producer. Call send with the topic name, the message key, and the event. To consume, write a component class with a method annotated at sign Kafka Listener, with the topics attribute set to the topic name and the group identifier set to your consumer group. Spring registers the method as a Kafka consumer and dispatches messages to it.

A few production grade details to know. Keys matter. Kafka partitions by key. Use a stable key, like the order identifier or the user identifier, so all events for the same entity land on the same partition and stay in order relative to each other. The consumer group identifier. Multiple instances of your service sharing the same group identifier split the partitions of a topic between them. That is how you scale consumption horizontally. Error handling. Spring kafka ships a default error handler that retries with backoff and then sends poison pill messages to a dead letter topic. Wire one up if you want anything more sophisticated than fail and skip the message. Acks and idempotence. For at least once delivery semantics, set acks equals all on the producer, and enable idempotence equals true. The defaults in modern spring kafka are reasonable, but always verify against your durability requirements.

Java Message Service in one paragraph. Java Message Service, abbreviated j m s, is the older java virtual machine messaging specification, typically used with brokers like ActiveMQ or i b m m q. Spring's Jms Template and at sign Jms Listener mirror the Kafka shapes. Java Message Service is the right choice when you are integrating with an existing enterprise message bus, or when you need transactional messaging tightly coupled to a Java Transaction Application Programming Interface transaction manager.

Spring AMQP in one paragraph. Spring AMQP is the Spring abstraction over the Advanced Message Queuing Protocol, version zero point nine point one, which in practice almost always means RabbitMQ. The shapes are again parallel. Rabbit Template for producing, at sign Rabbit Listener for consuming. The configuration involves exchanges, queues, and bindings, all defined as Spring beans. RabbitMQ shines for task queues with complex routing patterns, like work distribution, remote procedure call patterns, and fanout. Kafka shines for event streams with replay and long retention. Different tools for different jobs.

Now, packaging. Boot packages your application as an executable fat jar, also called an uber jar. The fat jar contains your code, every dependency, an embedded Tomcat, and a special launcher class, all in one file. You run it with java dash jar app dot jar. There is no external application server, no WEB dash INF directory, no separate war deployment.

The internal layout has your compiled classes and resources under BOOT dash INF slash classes, every dependency jar under BOOT dash INF slash lib, and the Spring Boot loader classes under org slash springframework slash boot slash loader at the root. The MANIFEST dot MF file points at the JarLauncher as the Main Class. Build it with m v n package or with the Gradle boot Jar task. The output is one self contained artifact you can copy anywhere with a java development kit.

Now, container deployment. There are two ways to put your Boot application in a container, both mainstream. The first way is the explicit Dockerfile approach. You start FROM a base image like eclipse temurin twenty one j r e alpine, you copy your fat jar into the image, you set the entrypoint to java dash jar, and you build the image. This works. The downside is that it copies the whole fat jar as one Docker layer, which means changing one line of your code re pushes every byte of every dependency layer.

The fix is the layered jar, which Boot enables by default since version two point three. A layered jar extracts the contents of the fat jar into four separate layers. Dependencies. Spring Boot loader. Snapshot dependencies. Application code. Each layer becomes a separate copy directive in your Dockerfile. Unchanged dependency layers stay cached. Only the small application code layer changes on a typical commit.

Even simpler than maintaining a Dockerfile, you can skip the Dockerfile entirely and use Cloud Native Buildpacks, which are built into Boot. The Maven command is m v n spring boot colon build dash image. The Gradle equivalent is boot Build Image. Either command produces an optimised, layered, secure open container initiative image, with no Dockerfile to maintain. Boot uses the Paketo buildpacks under the hood. The buildpacks pick a java development kit, apply best practice java virtual machine settings, and rebuild cleanly when only your source code changes. For most services, boot Build Image is the right default.

That wraps notebook eleven. You now have a Spring service you can deploy. Boot's auto configuration set up the runtime. At sign Configuration Properties made it environment portable. The actuator made it observable. The test slices made it testable. Testcontainers made the tests realistic. The spring kafka library plugged it into the message bus. And Cloud Native Buildpacks made it a container, with one command.

Notebook twelve, which is the final notebook of the track, turns one Spring service into a distributed system, with Spring Cloud. We will cover the configuration server for centralised configuration. Service discovery with Eureka. Spring Cloud Gateway as the application programming interface edge. Circuit breakers with Resilience four j. Distributed tracing via Micrometer and Open Telemetry. And Spring Cloud Stream, the higher level binder abstraction that sits on top of Kafka and RabbitMQ, and lets you write messaging code that does not depend on which broker is actually behind it.
